s not just similar to the S&L scandal, it was a severe relapse of the same underlying disease. And despite modest regulatory reforms, the disease remains uncured: top banks remain too big to manage, too big to regulate, and too big to fail.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aBanks and banking -- United States -- History. 0aBanks and bankingzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aFinancial crises -- United States -- History. 0aFinancial criseszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMortgage loans -- United States. 0aMortgage loanszUnited States. 0aSavings and Loan Bailout, 1989-1995. 0aSavings and loan association failures -- Economic aspects -- United States. 0aSavings and loan association failuresxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 21st Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311067250340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030020694440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300206944423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300206944/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles